final_thought: She wonders if the butterflies remember this place the way she remembers
  her great-grandmother's stories - a phantom migration to phantom forests, carried
  in the body long after the destination disappears
last_days_scenario: 'In March 2041, Maria sits in the empty oyamel grove where millions
  of monarchs once clustered like living orange snow. The trees are healthy, but silent.
  Her notebook lies open to her great-grandmother''s 1987 entries: "Arrived February
  14, covering twelve trees." Her own final entry reads simply: "Day 847. Still waiting."
  The traditional knowledge that took four generations to accumulate - when to expect
  arrivals, which trees they preferred, how weather patterns predicted cluster size
  - has become obsolete in a single decade. Like the monarchs whose genetic memory
  guides them to forests they''ve never seen, Maria carries inherited wisdom for a
  world that no longer exists. She tends the empty sanctuary, maintaining paths no
  one walks, a guardian of ghosts.'
